---
import DocsLayout from "../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro";
import {
  tiers,
  tierCount,
  goldenPath,
  errorCodes,
  uiOnlyOperations,
  renderInline,
} from "../../data/agent-tiers";
---

<DocsLayout
  title="AI Agents"
  description="How to build data pipelines with AI agents using the Datanika API. Discovery documents, golden-path loop, error handling, and common patterns."
>
  <h1 class="gradient-text">AI Agents</h1>
  <p class="text-lg text-slate-400 mb-8">
    Build complete data pipelines with Claude, GPT, or any LLM agent using the Datanika API.
  </p>

  <h2>Overview</h2>
  <p>
    Datanika's API is designed for autonomous AI agents. Two unauthenticated discovery documents
    tell the agent everything it needs to know, and a {tierCount}-tier capability stack lets it build,
    validate, and run pipelines without human intervention.
  </p>
  <p class="text-xs text-slate-500">
    The tier structure on this page is fetched at build time from <code>app.datanika.io/api/v1/meta/agent-tiers</code>, so
    it stays in sync with the live API. See <a href="https://github.com/datanika-io/datanika-landing/issues/108" target="_blank" rel="noopener">issue #108</a> for background.
  </p>

  <h2>Discovery Documents</h2>
  <p>These require no authentication. Point your agent here first.</p>

  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th>Document</th>
        <th>URL</th>
        <th>Purpose</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td><code>/llms.txt</code></td>
        <td><a href="https://app.datanika.io/llms.txt" target="_blank" rel="noopener">app.datanika.io/llms.txt</a></td>
        <td>Plain-text API discovery: base URL, auth format, rate limits, capability tiers</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><code>/api/v1/agent-guide.md</code></td>
        <td><a href="https://app.datanika.io/api/v1/agent-guide.md" target="_blank" rel="noopener">app.datanika.io/api/v1/agent-guide.md</a></td>
        <td>Strategy guide: 17-step golden-path loop, error codes, patterns</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><code>/api/v1/openapi.json</code></td>
        <td><a href="https://app.datanika.io/api/v1/openapi.json" target="_blank" rel="noopener">app.datanika.io/api/v1/openapi.json</a></td>
        <td>Full OpenAPI 3.0 spec with typed schemas and examples</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h2 id="capability-tiers">Capability Tiers</h2>
  <p>
    The API surface is organised as {tierCount} capability tiers. Each tier groups related endpoints an agent calls
    in sequence — discover what exists, then build, validate, execute, and observe. The full list below is the
    canonical source from core, not a handwritten mirror.
  </p>

  {tiers.map((tier) => (
    <section>
      <h3 id={`tier-${tier.number}`}>Tier {tier.number} — {tier.name}</h3>
      <p>{tier.summary}</p>
      {tier.capabilities.map((cap) => (
        <>
          <h4>{cap.name}</h4>
          <p>{cap.description}</p>
          <ul>
            {cap.endpoints.map((endpoint) => (
              <li><code>{endpoint}</code></li>
            ))}
          </ul>
        </>
      ))}
    </section>
  ))}

  <h2 id="golden-path">Golden-Path Loop ({goldenPath.length} steps)</h2>
  <p>
    The recommended endpoint-by-endpoint sequence for an agent building a pipeline from scratch. This is the
    long-form expansion of the capability tiers above — a concrete ordering an agent can follow verbatim.
  </p>
  <ol>
    {goldenPath.map((step) => (
      <li set:html={renderInline(step)} />
    ))}
  </ol>

  <h2>Error Handling</h2>
  <p>API endpoints return typed string error codes so the agent can branch on failures without regex-matching messages:</p>

  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th>Code</th>
        <th>Meaning</th>
        <th>Recovery Action</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      {errorCodes.map((err) => (
        <tr>
          <td><code>{err.code}</code></td>
          <td>{err.meaning}</td>
          <td set:html={renderInline(err.action)} />
        </tr>
      ))}
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h2>Idempotency</h2>
  <p>
    Add an <code>Idempotency-Key</code> header to POST requests. If a request with the same key was already
    processed within 24 hours, the original response is returned instead of creating a duplicate.
  </p>
  <pre><code>POST /api/v1/connections
Authorization: Bearer etf_...
Idempotency-Key: my-unique-key-123
Content-Type: application/json

{'{'}  "name": "Prod PG", "connection_type": "postgres", "config": {'{'} ... {'}'} {'}'}</code></pre>

  <h2>Common Patterns</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Compile before preview</strong> — <code>POST /compile</code> is cheap (no warehouse call). Always compile first to catch Jinja errors.</li>
    <li><strong>Use <code>?wait=true</code></strong> on run triggers instead of polling <code>GET /runs/{'{'}id{'}'}</code> in a loop. Default timeout 120s, max 300s.</li>
    <li><strong>Cancel + retry</strong> if a run appears stuck — <code>POST /runs/{'{'}id{'}'}/cancel</code> then re-trigger.</li>
    <li><strong>Introspect before building</strong> — list source tables and columns before writing the upload config. Don't guess table names.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>What the API Cannot Do</h2>
  <p>These operations are only available in the Datanika UI:</p>
  <ul>
    {uiOnlyOperations.map((op) => (
      <li set:html={renderInline(op)} />
    ))}
  </ul>
  <p>Do not attempt these via the API — there are no endpoints for them. Documenting this explicitly prevents agents from entering hallucination loops trying to find non-existent endpoints.</p>

  <h2>Rate Limits</h2>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th>Plan</th>
        <th>Requests/min</th>
        <th>Burst/sec</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>Free</td><td>30</td><td>5</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Pro</td><td>120</td><td>15</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Enterprise</td><td>300</td><td>30</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
  <p>Rate limit headers (<code>X-RateLimit-Remaining</code>, <code>Retry-After</code>) are included in every response.</p>

  <h2>Next Steps</h2>
  <div class="mt-4 grid gap-4 sm:grid-cols-2">
    <a href="/docs/api" class="block rounded-xl border border-slate-800 p-5 transition-colors hover:border-violet-500/50">
      <h3 class="!mt-0 text-white">API Reference</h3>
      <p class="text-sm text-slate-400 !mb-0">Full endpoint documentation with request/response examples.</p>
    </a>
    <a href="/docs/api-keys" class="block rounded-xl border border-slate-800 p-5 transition-colors hover:border-violet-500/50">
      <h3 class="!mt-0 text-white">API Keys</h3>
      <p class="text-sm text-slate-400 !mb-0">Create and manage API keys for agent access.</p>
    </a>
    <a href="/ai-agents" class="block rounded-xl border border-slate-800 p-5 transition-colors hover:border-violet-500/50">
      <h3 class="!mt-0 text-white">AI Agents Landing Page</h3>
      <p class="text-sm text-slate-400 !mb-0">Overview with code examples and competitor comparison.</p>
    </a>
    <a href="/blog/ai-agent-native" class="block rounded-xl border border-slate-800 p-5 transition-colors hover:border-violet-500/50">
      <h3 class="!mt-0 text-white">Announcement Post</h3>
      <p class="text-sm text-slate-400 !mb-0">Read the full announcement blog post.</p>
    </a>
  </div>
</DocsLayout>
